content:
    Wind-flicked and ruddy her young body glowed
    In sunny shallows, splashing them to spray;
    But when on rippled, silver sand she lay,

    In dream, again within the clean, cold hell
    Of glazed and aching silence he was trapped;
    And, closing in, the blank walls of his cell

    Still bathed in its moonlight slumber, the little white house by the cedar
    Stands silent against the red dawn;
    And nothing I know of who

    Only the footprints of the partridge run
    Over the billowy drifts on the mountain-side;
    And now on level wings the brown birds glide
